DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(90)90021-S
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669090021S
AB  - This paper is divided into two parts. In the first part (section 2) we present a model of a smaller economy which we use to evaluate, in a simple comparative static framework, the roles of exchange-rate flexibility, capital mobility and indexation in the transmission of foreign impulses from abroad. In the second part (section 3) we examine, in some detail, how expectations about foreign disturbances affect the way in which policies abroad are transmitted to the home economy. We analyse three distinct cases: the case of a fully anticipated permanent monetary and fiscal expansion abroad, the case of an anticipated permanent change in policy abroad which is not realised and the case of an unanticipated policy change abroad.
ER  - 

